`crates/ctx-cage/src/bwrap/` is the sandbox-configuration boundary: it turns a `BwrapConfig` value into the exact `bwrap` argv used to launch the cage process, and defines every path constant and struct field that describes the sandbox's mount layout. Depending on this module gets you `build_bwrap_args` (pure, deterministic, no I/O) plus the `BwrapConfig` type and cage-side path constants; no other module should construct bwrap flags directly.

`config.rs` and `build.rs` are a single coupled unit disguised as two files: every `BwrapConfig` field has a corresponding `add_*` helper in `build.rs`, and the two must change together — the doc rationale for a field (why `mask_file` can't be `/dev/null`, why `resolv_conf` can't be absent) lives in `config.rs` but the enforcement of that rationale is in `build.rs`'s argument ordering. `mod.rs` restates the two load-bearing ADRs (ADR-046 target_root identity binding, ADR-049 resolv.conf stub) as the authoritative doc surface — treat its doc comment as the spec both submodules must satisfy. `discover.rs` is a separate concern: it walks the target project's `crates/*` to build a `DiscoveredCrates` list (sorted, relative paths) used elsewhere to decide what gets tmpfs-overlaid; it doesn't touch `BwrapConfig` or `build_bwrap_args` directly, so changes there are largely independent of the config/build pair.

Invariant spanning the subtree: the cage-side path constants defined in `config.rs` are the only strings `build.rs` is allowed to bind targets to, and any runtime consumer (lifecycle code, `/opt/cage/rules.md`) must agree on those exact strings — moving one requires updating all three simultaneously.